pidgins and creoles spread over the region. Other chapters investigate the typology of salient linguistic features of the area, including vowel harmony, noun inflection, verb indexing (also known as agreement), complex morphologies, and the syntax of complex predicates. Issues relating to genealogical ancestry, areal contact and language endangerment receive equal attention. With historical connections both to Eurasia’s pastoral-based empires as well as to ancient population movements into the Americas, the steppes, taiga forests, tundra and coastal fringes of northern Asia offer a complex and fascinating object of linguistic investigation.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aMandschu-Tungusische Sprachfamilie. 4aMongolische Sprachfamilie. 4aSibirien. 4aTurksprachen. 4aUralische Sprachen.  aNative Languages of Siberia & Asia's North Pacific Rim, Uralic, Mongolic, Tungusic, Turkic Language Families.1 aBerge, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBugaeva, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDunn, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aForsberg, Ulla-Maija, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGruzdeva, Ekaterina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJanhunen, Juha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNikolaeva, Irina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNémeth, Michał, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOskolskaya, Sofia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSalminen, Tapani, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVajda, Edward , eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/